# Functionalities 
Reflects expected functionalities necessary for each modules.  

## Common capabilties to all providers
- Generate SSH keys
- n numbers of masters and n numbers of workers
- Add or remove VMs 
- Separate masters/workers objects
- Per-role:
    - CPU / RAM / disk
    - optional IP/MAC
    - extra disks (structured)
- Cloud-init choice:
    - Set username for a root priviled user with its ssh pub key
- Optional vars pass to cloud-init:
  - k3s
  - rke2
  - Specific to k3s/rke2:
      - Generating a Token
      - Pulling Kubeconfig
  - ansible-pull

## Specific Azure model
- NSG rules 

## Specific Libvirt model
- local connexion by default or ssh connexion to QEMU
- Per-role:
    - optional IP/MAC
- Network config
    - NAT or Bridge
    - DHCP or Static

## Specific OVH model
- Public-IP-based operator access for SSH, inventory, and kubeconfig retrieval
- Optional private networking for cluster internal traffic via `network.cidr`
- Deterministic private IP assignment from `network.cidr`
- Separate masters and workers, with multi-master supported when `network.cidr` is set
- Kubernetes API exposed through an OVH load balancer when private networking is enabled
- Load balancer endpoint can be advertised by floating IP or externally managed DNS name
- Optional exact-match floating-IP cleanup helper for load-balancer destroy leftovers
- Current limitations:
    - inventory remains public-IP based even when a private network exists
    - private networking and the kube-api load balancer are currently coupled
    - custom root disk sizing not supported yet
    - extra disks not supported yet
    - some multi-node readiness scenarios can still be inconsistent


# Test Scenario to be run

| Provider | Infra                 | k8s type  | Config  | 
| ---      | ---                   | ---       | ---     |
| AZ       | 1 masters             | k3s       | default |
| AZ       | 3 masters / 2 workers | k3s       | default |
| AZ       | 1 masters             | rke2      | default |
| AZ       | 3 masters / 2 workers | rke2      | default |
| KVM      | 1 masters             | k3s       | default |
| KVM      | 3 masters / 2 workers | k3s       | default |
| KVM      | 1 masters             | rke2      | default |
| KVM      | 3 masters / 2 workers | rke2      | default |
| OVH      | 1 masters             | k3s       | default |
| OVH      | 1 masters / 2 workers | k3s       | default |
| OVH      | 3 masters             | k3s       | default |
| OVH      | 1 masters             | rke2      | default |
| OVH      | 1 masters / 2 workers | rke2      | default |
| OVH      | 3 masters             | rke2      | default |

OVH scenarios currently also use `network.cidr`, deterministic private IP assignment, and the kube-api load-balancer flow.
